<section>
  <title>An Abstract Look at Intervals</title>

  <p>
    First, we can consider an interval in geometric terms as the point <m>(\underline{a},\overline{a})</m> in <m>\R^{2}</m>.
    Some examples are:
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-intervals">
    <caption></caption>
    <image>
      <shortdescription>
      </shortdescription>
      <latex-image>
       <![CDATA[
       \begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[->] (-4.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node [above right] {$x$}; \foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node [below] {\x};
 \draw[->] (0,-4.5) -- (0,4.5) node [above right] {$y$};
\foreach \y in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4} \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node [left] {\y};
\draw[<->] (-4.5,-4.5) -- (4.5,4.5);
\draw[very thick] (3,0) -- (4,0);
\draw[dashed] (3,0) -- (3,4);
\fill (3,4) circle[radius=2pt];
\draw[very thick] (-2,0) -- (1,0);
\draw[dashed] (-2,0) -- (-2,1);
\fill (-2,1) circle[radius=2pt];
\draw[dashed] (2,0) -- (2,2); \fill(2,2) circle[radius=2pt];
\end{tikzpicture}
       ]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    And since for intervals <m>\underline{a}\leq \overline{a}</m>, then all intervals can be represented as points on or above the line <m>y=x</m>.
    All thin intervals are on the line <m>y=x</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Note also, that if we think of intervals in this way that addition is the same as vector addition.
    That is, as an example
    <me>
      [3,4] + [-2,1] = [1,5]
    </me>
  </p>

  <p>
    Question: Is the set of all intervals with addition and scalar multiplication defined as ??? a vector space?
  </p>
</section>